  "text": "<html>\r\n    <head>\r\n    <style>\r\n        .unselectable {\r\n          -webkit-user-select: none;\r\n          -webkit-touch-callout: none;\r\n          -moz-user-select: none;\r\n          -ms-user-select: none;\r\n          user-select: none;\r\n        }\r\n      <\/style>\r\n      <\/head>\r\n\r\n<body class=\"unselectable\">\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">WHAT ARE THE FIGURES OF SPEECH?<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A figure of speech is a deviation from the ordinary use of words in order to increase their&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">effectiveness. Basically, it is a figurative language that may consist of a single word or&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">phrase. It may be a simile, a metaphor or personification to convey the meaning other&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">than the literal meaning.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">TYPES OF FIGURES OF SPEECH<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">1. SIMILE<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">In simile two unlike things are explicitly compared. For example, &ldquo;She is like a fairy&rdquo;. A&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">simile is introduced by words such as like, so, as etc.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">2. METAPHOR<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">It is an informal or implied simile in which words like, as, so are omitted. For example,&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&ldquo;He is like a lion (Simile) &ldquo;and &ldquo;He is a lion (metaphor)&rdquo;. In the following examples,&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">metaphors are underlined.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; She is a star of our family.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; The childhood of the world; the anger of the tempest; the deceitfulness of&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">the riches: wine is a mocker.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; She is now in the sunset of her days.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">3. PERSONIFICATION<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Personification is an attribution of personal nature, intelligence or character to inanimate&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">objects or abstract notions. For example, in some phrases we use, the furious storm, the&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">thirsty ground, and the pitiless cold. Some other examples are:<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Little sorrows sit and weep. (Boccaccio)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The dish ran away with the spoon. (Blake)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">4. METONYMY<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Metonymy is meant for a change of name. It is a substitute of the thing names for the&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">thing meant. Following examples will clarify the concept.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; The pen is mightier than the sword.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; From the cradle to the grave. = from childhood to death.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; I have never read Milton. = the works of Milton.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">5. APOSTROPHE<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">It is a direct address to some inanimate thing or some abstract idea as if it were living&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">person or some absent person as if it were present. Example, &quot;Boy&#39;s mother loved him&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">very much.&quot;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">6. HYPERBOLE<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Hyperbole is a statement made emphatic by overstatement. For example, &ldquo;Virtues as the&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">sands of the shore.&rdquo;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">7. SYNECDOCHE<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Synecdoche is the understanding of one thing by means of another. Here, a part is used to&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">designate the whole or the whole to designate a part. For example, &ldquo;I have the Viceroy,&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">love the man.&rdquo;, and &ldquo;All hands (crew) at work.&rdquo;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">8. TRANSFERRED EPITHETS<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">In transferred epithets, the qualifying objective is transferred from a person to a thing as&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">in phrases. For example, &ldquo;sleepless night&rdquo;, &ldquo;sunburn mirth&rdquo;, and &ldquo;melodious plain&rdquo;.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">9. EUPHEMISM<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">By using the euphemism, we speak in agreeable and favorable terms of some person,&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">object or event which is ordinarily considered unpleasant and disagreeable. For example,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; He is telling us a fairy tale. (a lie)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; He has fallen asleep. (he is dead)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">10. IRONY OR SARCASM<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">In this mode of speech, the real meanings of the words used are different from the&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">intended meanings. For example, the child of cobbler has no shoe.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">11. PUN<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This consists of a play on the various meanings of a word. Its effect is often ludicrous.&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">For example,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Is life worth living? It depends upon the liver.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Obviously, the constitution is against prostitution and congress is against&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">progress. (con means against and pro means for)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">12. EPIGRAM<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">It is a brief pointed saying. It couples words which apparently contradict each other. The&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">language of the epigram is remarkable for its brevity. Examples are as under:<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; The child is the father of the man. (Wordsworth)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Fools rush in where angels fear to tread.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; The art lies in concealing art.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Silence is sometimes more eloquent than words.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Conspicuous by its absence.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">13. ANTITHESIS<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">In antithesis, a striking opposition or contrast of words is made in the same sentence in&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">order to secure emphasis. For example,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; To err is human, to forgive divine.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Give every man thy ear, but few thy voice.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">14. OXYMORON<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">It is a figure of speech which combines two seemingly contradictory or incongruous&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">words for sharp emphasis or effect. For example,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; &ldquo;darkness visible&rdquo; (Milton);<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; &ldquo;make haste slowly&rdquo; (Suetonius)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; &ldquo;loving hate&rdquo; (Romeo and Juliet)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">15. LITOTES<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">It is the opposite of hyperbole. Here an affirmative is conveyed by negation of the&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">opposite. For example,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; He is no dullard.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; I am not a little<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; He is not a bad sort.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">16. INTERROGATION<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This is a rhetorical mode of affirming or denying something more strongly than could be&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">done in ordinary language. Examples,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Who is here so base that would be a bondman?<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Who is here so rude that would not be a Roman?<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Who is here so vile that will not love his country? (Shakespeare)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">17. EXCLAMATION<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">It is used for strong expression of feelings. For examples, O lift me as a wave, a leaf, a&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">cloud I fall upon the thorns of life; I bleed!<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">18. CLIMAX<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">It is an arrangement of a series of ideas in the order of increasing importance. For&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">example, &ldquo;What a piece of work man! How noble in reason, how infinite in faculties! In&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">action, how like an angel!&rdquo;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">19. ANTICLIMAX OR BATHOS<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This is the opposite to climax and signifies a ludicrous descent from the higher to the&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">lower.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; A man so various, that he seemed to be. Not one, but all mankind&rsquo;s&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">epitome; who in the course of one revolving moon; was lawyer, statesman,&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">fiddler, and buffoon.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">20. ALLITERATION<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The repetition of the same letter or syllable at the beginning of two or more words is&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">called alliteration. For example,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; By apt Alliteration&rsquo;s artful a<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Glittering through the gloomy g<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; The furrow follows f<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">21. ONOMATOPOEIA<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The formation of a word whose sound is made to suggest or echo the sense as in cuckoo,&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">bang, growl, hiss.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; The moan of doves in immemorial elms and murmur of innumerable bees.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; Rend with the tremendous sound your ears asunder with guns, drum,&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">trumpet, blunderbuss, and thunder.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">22. CIRCUMLOCUTION<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">This consists of expressing some fact or idea in a roundabout way, instead of stating it at&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">once. For example,<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; The viewless couriers of the air. =(the wind)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&bull; That statement of his was purely an effort of imagination. = (a fiction)<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">23. TAUTOLOGY OR PLEONASM<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Tautology is meant for repeating the same fact or idea in different words. For example,&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&ldquo;It is the privilege and birthright of every man to express his ideas without any fear.&rdquo;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">PUME Examples<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&ldquo; Olu hissed, slammed the door and dashed out screaming.&rdquo; The dominant figure of in the above sentence<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. zeugma<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">B. oxymoron<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C. hyperbole<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D. onomatopoeia<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Onomatopoeia<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">An insincere literacy work is known as a ___.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. parody<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">B. paradox<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C. satire<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D. pathos<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Parody<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&quot;See! how she leans her cheek upon herhand: O! that! wore a glove upon that hand<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">That I might touch that cheek.&rdquo;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The predominant figure of speech in these lines is___.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. conceit<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">B. apostrophe<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C. caricature<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D. smile<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">B<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Apostrophe<\/span><\/strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">: This is a figure of speech that addresses somebody or something that is not present at the point of speaking as if the person or thing is present and listening.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Let my love like incense from Abel&rsquo;s palms rise to the golden temple of your face&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The above contains both___.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. A simile and a paradox<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">B. A simile and a litotes<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C. A simile and a metaphor<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D. A simile and a personification<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A simile and a metaphor<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The line &quot;Your mouth, O Katty, is a museum with many monuments&quot; is both<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. metaphoric and hyperbolic<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">B. a synecdoche and a metonymy<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C. metaphoric and epigrammatic<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D. a metaphor and an allusion<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">metaphoric and hyperbolic<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">In the same lines, the device adopted in talking of fortune is___.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. pomposity<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">B. analogy<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C. axiom<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D. personification<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Personification<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The title of Umeh&#39;s Ambassador is Poverty is___.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. a repetition<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">B. a simile<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">C. an alliteration<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D. an irony<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">D<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:8pt; line-height:108%; font-size:12pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">an irony<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n<\/body>\r\n\r\n<\/html>",
  "chapIndex": "FIGURES OF SPEECH"
}